arch:property.oc:show_val: Area west of Subflooring Locus 11B and east of Suspended Floor Locus 13.

This is a soil deposit filling the area below the level of the collapsed Suspended Floor of the Hypocaust Chamber. It covers both the surviving hypocaust tile columns and the lower portion of the Locus 4 collapsed superstructure from Wall Locus 2. The deposit consisted primarily of very fine soils, ranged in size between clay and sand, and was permeated throughout with a large quantity of ash. The Munsell Color range was between 10YR 4/2 (Dark Grayish Brown) and 3/2 (Very Dark Grayish Brown). Excavation of this stratum yielded quite a few small finds, including 6 coins and 4 pieces of jewelry. A fragment from a possible terracotta incense burner was also found near the bottom of the stratum. This deposit appears to be the result of both destruction and sedimentation. Some of the material, such as the ash, is likely to have been present in the hypocaust substructure at the time of the collapse event. This material likely became disturbed and intermingled with additional sediment as a result of the destruction of the Suspended Floor and subsequent erosion activity.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of the West Colonnade directly on top of the Hexagonal Pavement and into the West Cryptoporticus. The accumulation of early debris during this phase contains large amounts of architectural elements mixed with fill and sedimentation washed over the east perimeter wall. Some collapse is also seen in the south of the East Triple Colonnade.
